- tested wtih cocos3.14.1, visual studio 15 and win8.1 universal

at js_CCNode_unschedule :: cocos2d_specifics.cpp

if the target is current target, sched->unscheule() doesn't remove the unscheduled hash element.
but js target is released by JSScheduleWrapper::removeTargetForJSObject

```c++
sched->unschedule(schedule_selector(JSScheduleWrapper::scheduleFunc), target);
JSScheduleWrapper::removeTargetForJSObject(obj, target);
```

at this point if we schedule with new target,
the released memory address can be assigned to the new target.

js_CCNode_schedule or js_CCNode_scheduleOnce or js_cocos2dx_CCNode_scheduleUpdate,
js_CCScheduler_scheduleUpdateForTarget or .... 

```c++
tmpCobj = new (std::nothrow) JSScheduleWrapper(thisValue);
```

and bomb!
the target has the same address in the hash elemnt->target which is released right ago.
and if the new target doens't run yet, ASSERT happens.

```c++
// at func void Scheduler::schedule(....) : CCScheduler.cpp
...
ASSSERT(element->paused == paused, "element's paused should be paused.");
...
```

here is the test javascript code.

```javascript
var scene = new cc.Scene();
var node = new cc.Node();
scene.addChild(node);
node.schFunc = function() {
	node.unschedule(node.schFunc); // released but not removed in the hash
	var subNode = new cc.Node();
	subNode.schFunc = function() {
		cc.log("I'm sub");
		subNode.removeFromParent();
	};
	subNode.scheduleOnce(subNode.schFunc, 0.01); // yeah! the target address is re-assigned here at native!
	node.addChild(subNode);
};

scene.runAction(cc.sequence(
	cc.callFunc(function() {
		node.schedule(node.schFunc, 0.01);
	}, scene),
	cc.delayTime(0.1)
).repeat(1000));

cc.director.pushScene(scene);
````

